    <h2>1) What is the URL of the website?</h2>
    <p><a href="https://bluewaterbaltimore.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://bluewaterbaltimore.org/</a></p>

    <h2>2) What is the name of the website?</h2>
    <p>Blue Water Baltimore</p>

    <h2>3) Who is the site's target audience?</h2>
    <p>Baltimore-area residents, volunteers, donors, and people interested in clean water and environmental health.</p>

    <h2>4) How is the site organized?</h2>
    <p>Clear top navigation (About, Programs, Take Action, Blog, etc.). Homepage sections highlight mission, news, events, and donate options.</p>

    <h2>5) CRAP Design Principle (one example)</h2>
    <p><strong>Contrast:</strong> Dark logo/accents on a light background help buttons and headings stand out.</p>

    <h2>6) Accessibility Checker (Audit Score)</h2>
    <p>I ran the homepage in <strong>Lighthouse</strong> and saw an Accessibility score of <strong>91/100</strong>. (Tool used: Lighthouse.)</p>

    <h2>7) Effectiveness</h2>
    <p>Effective: I searched “water report” and quickly found relevant reports from prior years.</p>

    <h2>8) Efficiency</h2>
    <p>Efficient navigation and working links; tasks like donating or finding info are quick.</p>

    <h2>9) Engagement</h2>
    <p>Professional and friendly photos with a water/green palette that fits an environmental nonprofit.</p>

    <h2>10) Recommendation</h2>
    <p>Add short video on the landing section (in addition to photos) to increase engagement; also ensure every image has alt text.</p>

